re how science is defined; how evidence is produced, used, and interpreted; and how science shapes the imagination and vice versa. Exploring the development of racial photography wherever it took place, including countries like France and England, Morris-Reich pays special attention to the German and Jewish contexts of scientific racism. Through careful reconstruction of individual cases, conceptual genealogies, and patterns of practice, he compares the intended roles of photography with its actual use in scientific argumentation. He examines the diverse ways it was used to establish racial ideologies—as illustrations of types, statistical data, or as self-evident record of racial signs. Altogether, Morris-Reich visits this troubling history to outline important truths about the roles of visual argumentation, imagination, perception, aesthetics, epistemology, and ideology within scientific study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGermansxRace identity. 0aJewszEurope, CentralxIdentity. 0aJewszEurope, EasternxIdentity. 0aPhotography in ethnologyxHistory. 0aPhotography in ethnologyzEuropexHistory. 0aPhotography in ethnologyzPalestinexHistory. 0aPhotographyxScientific applicationsxHistory. 0aPhotographyxScientific applicationszEuropexHistory. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106904390 cprintz978022632074840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226320915423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226320915/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles